{"title_page": "Jorge Cadete", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name = Jorge Cadete\n|image = \n|fullname = Jorge Paulo Cadete Santos Reis\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|8|27|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Pemba, Mozambique|Pemba]], [[Portuguese Mozambique|Mozambique]]\n|height = 1.80 m\n|position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n|youthyears1 = 1983\u20131984 | youthclubs1 = Acad\u00e9mica Santar\u00e9m\n|youthyears2 = 1984\u20131987 | youthclubs2 = [[Sporting CP]]\n|years1 = 1987\u20131995 | clubs1 = [[Sporting CP]] | caps1 = 164 | goals1 = 62\n|years2 = 1988\u20131989 | clubs2 = \u2192 [[Vit\u00f3ria F.C.|Vit\u00f3ria Set\u00fabal]] (loan) | caps2 = 29 | goals2 = 8\n|years3 = 1994\u20131995 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Brescia Calcio|Brescia]] (loan) | caps3 = 13 | goals3 = 1\n|years4 = 1996\u20131997 | clubs4 = [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] | caps4 = 37 | goals4 = 30\n|years5 = 1997\u20131998 | clubs5 = [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]] | caps5 = 36 | goals5 = 8\n|years6 = 1999\u20132003 | clubs6 = [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] | caps6 = 19 | goals6 = 3\n|years7 = 2000 | clubs7 = \u2192 [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (loan) | caps7 = 7 | goals7 = 0\n|years8 = 2000\u20132001 | clubs8 = \u2192 [[C.F. Estrela da Amadora|Estrela Amadora]] (loan) | caps8 = 28 | goals8 = 2\n|years9 = 2004 | clubs9 = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] | caps9 = 5 | goals9 = 0\n|years10 = 2004\u20132005 | clubs10 = [[C.D. Pinhalnovense|Pinhalnovense]] | caps10 = 4 | goals10 = 0\n|years11 = 2005\u20132007 | clubs11 = S\u00e3o Marcos | caps11 = | goals11 = \n|totalcaps = 342 | totalgoals = 114\n|nationalyears1 = 1989 | nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 2 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n|nationalyears2 = 1990\u20131998 | nationalteam2 =[[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] | nationalcaps2 = 33 | nationalgoals2 = 5\n}}\n'''Jorge Paulo Cadete Santos Reis''' (born 27 August 1968), known as '''Cadete''', is a Portuguese former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]].\n\nBorn to [[White African#Former Portuguese colonies|Portuguese parents in Mozambique]], he was groomed in [[Sporting CP|Sporting]]'s prolific youth system, and later was noted while at [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] as he led the goalscoring charts in [[1996\u201397 Scottish Premier Division|1996\u201397]].\n\nCadete amassed [[Primeira Liga]] totals of 233 matches and 73 goals over 12 seasons. A [[Portugal national football team|Portuguese international]] throughout the 90s, he represented the nation at [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 1996]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career and Sporting===\nBorn in [[Pemba, Mozambique|Pemba]], [[Portuguese Mozambique]], Cadete began his footballing career with Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Acad\u00e9mica de Santar\u00e9m at age 15, scoring an impressive 43 goals in just 18 games.<ref name=Expresso>{{cite news|url=https://tribunaexpresso.pt/a-casa-as-costas/2017-10-14-Jorge-Cadete-Nao-sou-nenhum-deficiente.-Tenho-duas-maos-dois-bracinhos-nao-desisti-de-dar-a-volta-a-tudo|title=Jorge Cadete: \u201cN\u00e3o sou nenhum deficiente. Tenho duas m\u00e3os, dois bracinhos, n\u00e3o desisti de dar a volta a tudo\u201d|trans-title=Jorge Cadete: \u201cI'm not handicapped. I have two hands, two little arms, I have not given up on turning things around\u201d|newspaper=[[Expresso (newspaper)|Expresso]]|first=Alexandra|last=Sim\u00f5es de Abreu|language=pt|date=14 October 2017|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref> His exploits alerted [[Primeira Liga]] giants [[Sporting CP]] and [[S.L. Benfica]], with the former winning the race to sign the promising youngster.<ref name=\"Celta\">{{cite web|url=http://www.yojugueenelcelta.com/2008/04/jorge-cadete.html|title=Jorge Cadete|publisher=Yo Jugu\u00e9 en el Celta|language=es|date=8 April 2008|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref>\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[File:Scpxbelenenses.gif|thumb|left|300px|Jorge Cadete with [[Sporting Clube de Portugal]]]] -->\n\nCadete broke into the senior team in [[1987\u201388 Primeira Liga|1987\u201388]], starting in four of his six appearances and subsequently being sent on loan to fellow league club [[Vit\u00f3ria F.C.]] for [[1988\u201389 Primeira Liga|the following season]], helping the [[Set\u00fabal]]-based side to the fifth place. He thus returned to [[Lisbon]], where he would play for the following five years uninterrupted and in the [[1992\u201393 Primeira Liga|1992\u201393 campaign]] he was the national championship's top-scorer with 18 goals.<ref name=Expresso/>\n\nTowards the end of his time at Sporting, Cadete was loaned out again in November 1994, this time to Italy's [[Brescia Calcio]]. He only managed one [[Serie A]] goal during his stint,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contra-ataque.it/2016/05/27/cadete-brescia-europei-bidone.html|title=Pacchi Europei: Cadete, il Brescia peggiore di sempre e la comparsata ad Euro \u201996|trans-title=European parcels: Cadete, worst-ever Brescia and cameo at Euro \u201996|publisher=Contra Ataque|first=Salvatore|last=Lavino|language=it|date=27 May 2016|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> returning subsequently to the [[Est\u00e1dio Jos\u00e9 Alvalade]] and featuring in [[1995 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|the first leg]] of the [[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]] against [[FC Porto]] in August 1995.<ref name=Supercup>{{cite web|url=http://www.zerozero.pt/jogo.php?id=47003|title=Sporting 0\u20130 FC Porto|publisher=Zerozero|language=pt|date=6 August 1995|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy early 1996, especially after the sacking of manager [[Bobby Robson]] and the arrival of [[Carlos Queiroz]], Cadete was completely out of favour at Sporting and made no more appearances for them. He amassed competitive totals for the club of 203 games and 81 goals.<ref name=Expresso/>\n\n===Celtic===\nOn 24 February 1996, Cadete was introduced at [[Celtic Park]], [[Glasgow]] to supporters before [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]'s league match against [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/celtics-four-sight-1321029.html|title=Celtic's four sight|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|first=David|last=Dick|date=25 February 1996|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref> However, due to lengthy negotiations between Celtic and Sporting and issues with registering the player, his transfer was not finalised until April, and turned out to be controversial: despite being signed prior to the transfer deadline, the [[Scottish Football Association]] delayed processing his registration in time for the [[Scottish Cup]] semi-finals against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] at [[Hampden Park]], and following a complaint from Celtic chairman [[Fergus McCann]], SFA chief [[Jim Farry]] was eventually relieved of his duties after being found guilty of deliberately holding back the player's registration.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/288283.stm Football SFA boss suspended]; [[BBC Sport]], 1 March 1999</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/farry-s-fall-from-grace-1-1304383|title=Farry's fall from grace|newspaper=[[The Scotsman]]|date=21 February 2009|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref> His eventual debut came at home against [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] as he came [[Substitute (association football)|off the bench]] to score his team's fifth goal in a 5\u20130 win, thus becoming an instant hit;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/cadete-boosts-celtic-title-chase-1302941.html|title=Cadete boosts Celtic title chase|newspaper=The Independent|first=David|last=McKinney|date=1 April 1996|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref> the loud roar generated by the fans celebrating his goal blew out [[BBC Radio 5 Live|BBC Radio 5]]'s microphones, who had been covering the game UK wide on radio, and they went off air for a short time until it was repaired.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celticunderground.net/debut-days-jorge-cadete/|title=Debut Days \u2013 Jorge Cadete|publisher=The Celtic Underground|date=19 November 2016|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nCadete's [[1996\u201397 Scottish Premier Division|only full season]] in [[Scotland]] was unarguably the greatest of his career, with the player finishing the year as the country's top scorer with 38 goals in 47 appearances in all competitions, without the aid of [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kicks]].<ref name=Scorer>{{cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/celtic/leeds-tried-to-sign-jorge-cadete-from-celtic-for-9m-1-4588343|title=Leeds \u2018tried to sign Jorge Cadete from Celtic for \u00a39m\u2019|newspaper=The Scotsman|first=Craig|last=Forbes|date=16 October 2017|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> Despite this, his team lost the league championship to arch-rivals Rangers, and he played his last match against [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], bowing to the fans before kissing the turf.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/jan/29/jorge-cadete-portugal-celtic-state-benefits|title=Jorge Cadete: the former Celtic striker who lost everything|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|first=Ewan|last=Murray|date=29 January 2014|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nAlong with [[Pierre van Hooijdonk]] and [[Paolo Di Canio]], Cadete became embroiled in contractual disputes with the club, and was labelled as one of the \"Three Amigos\" by McCann. He remained a Celtic player over the summer, but fled back to Portugal citing mental health issues and a failure to adjust to life in Scotland without his family; his requests for a transfer were eventually granted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/mccann-knocks-three-amigos-1-526878|title=McCann knocks three amigos|newspaper=The Scotsman|date=10 May 2001|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===To Spain and beyond===\nAfter failing to show for pre-season training, Cadete was transferred to [[RC Celta de Vigo]] of [[La Liga]] for a fee of around \u00a33,500,000.<ref name=\"Celta\"/> He played [[1997\u201398 La Liga|one full season]] for the [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicians]], and scored on his debut on 27 September 1997 in a 3\u20133 draw away to [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-no-end-in-sight-to-milan-slump-1241850.html|title=Football: No end in sight to Milan slump|newspaper=The Independent|first=Rupert|last=Metcalf|date=28 September 1997|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> He moved to Benfica alongside former Celtic teammate van Hooijdonk in January 1999, and a year later he returned to the United Kingdom, joining newly promoted [[Premier League]] side [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] on loan until the end of [[1999\u20132000 FA Premier League|the campaign]]; he made his debut as a substitute in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] at [[Valley Parade]], and was described as having an \"instant impact\" in that game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/feb/28/match.bradford|title=Cadete has instant effect on Bradford's survival instincts|newspaper=The Guardian|first=Adam|last=Sills|date=28 February 2000|accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor [[2000\u201301 Primeira Liga|2000\u201301]], Cadete was loaned to the Lisbon-based [[C.F. Estrela da Amadora]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/futebol/nacional/interior.aspx?content_id=37070|title=Cadete e Lu\u00eds Carlos assinam pelo Estrela da Amadora|trans-title=Cadete and Lu\u00eds Carlos sign for Estrela da Amadora|newspaper=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]|language=pt|date=23 June 2000|accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref> As newly promoted Scottish side [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] looked for a striker to bolster its chances of top-flight survival, he almost made a return to the country, but the proposed January switch fell through and he remained in Estrela, subsequently seeing out his Benfica contract after claiming unpaid wages.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/benfica/detalhe/cadete-vai-rescindir-contrato-com-o-benfica|title=Cadete vai rescindir contrato com o Benfica|trans-title=Cadete will terminate contract with Benfica|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=24 October 2000|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement and return to football and Scotland===\nFollowing his release from Benfica, Cadete found himself without a club. After failing to find a new team he retired from football at the relatively young age of 33, going on to make an appearance on the celebrity version of the [[Big Brother (TV series)|Big Brother]] reality TV show.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cmjornal.xl.pt/noticia.aspx?channelid=00000133-0000-0000-0000-000000000133&contentid=B29B4580-947A-426F-B890-D4256A978E63|title=Cadete luta contra falta de dinheiro|trans-title=Cadete struggles against shortage of money|newspaper=[[Correio da Manh\u00e3]]|language=pt|date=29 November 2008|accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[File:jorgeII.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] Jorge Cadete on signing for Partick Thistle]] -->\nAt the start of 2003\u201304 season, aged 35, Cadete decided to come out of retirement. He returned to Scotland to make a guest appearance on [[Tam Cowan]]'s Scottish football show \"[[Offside (TV Show)|Offside]]\", where he spoke of his love for Celtic and how he regretted leaving; he also invited Celtic boss [[Martin O'Neill]] to give him a trial for his former club.\n\nCadete's return to the public eye in Scotland prompted rookie co-managers [[Gerry Britton]] and [[Derek Whyte]] to take a gamble on the striker. He signed a short-term contract for top division relegation battlers [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] in late January 2004, ending his 18-month exile from the game; the move was controversial however, as he had already agreed to sign for [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]], even being photographed in the team shirt by the media.\n\nCadete made his debut for the ''Jags'' on 22 February against former club Celtic, and received a mixed reception, with jeers from some Celtic fans as he came off the bench due to the manner of his departure six years earlier.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/scot_prem/3505203.stm Partick Thistle 1\u20134 Celtic]; BBC Sport, 22 February 2004</ref> Shortly after, he returned to old ways when he reported back for training 24 hours late, and was subsequently disciplined by the club;<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/3527311.stm Cadete back with Thistle]; BBC Sport, 3 March 2004</ref> he did not manage to score for Thistle in four months, and was not offered a contract extension.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/3495529.stm Thistle let Cadete go]; BBC Sport, 20 March 2004</ref>\n\n===Later years===\nCadete returned to his country in the [[2004\u201305 Segunda Divis\u00e3o B|2004\u201305 campaign]], joining [[Portuguese Second Division|third division]]'s [[C.D. Pinhalnovense]]. He cited the major factor in signing for the club was working with coach [[Paco Fortes]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cmjornal.pt/desporto/detalhe/nova-etapa-para-cadete|title=Nova etapa para Cadete|trans-title=New lease of life for Cadete|newspaper=Correio da Manh\u00e3|language=pt|date=6 August 2004|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the following two years, Cadete played amateur football in the [[Beja, Portugal|Beja]] region, with FC S\u00e3o Marcos in S\u00e3o Marcos da Ataboeira, [[Castro Verde]], being rejoined by some former professionals in the country, including Benfica and [[S.C. Farense]]'s [[Hassan Nader]]. After retiring, he faced severe economic problems.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cmjornal.pt/desporto/detalhe/jorge-cadete-sem-dinheiro-e-em-casa-dos-pais|title=Jorge Cadete sem dinheiro e em casa dos pais|trans-title=Jorge Cadete with no money and in his parents' house|newspaper=Correio da Manh\u00e3|language=pt|date=22 January 2014|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian\"/>\n\nOn 23 July 2015, Cadete was appointed [[director of football]] of U.F.C. Almeirim in [[Santar\u00e9m, Portugal|Santar\u00e9m]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/detalhe/jorge-cadete-dirigente-em-almeirim-964125.html|title=Jorge Cadete dirigente em Almeirim|trans-title=Jorge Cadete director in Almeirim|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=23 July 2015|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nCadete won 33 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for the [[Portugal national football team|Portuguese national team]] scoring five goals, 22 while at Sporting, nine while at Celtic and two as a Celta player. His first game came on 29 August 1990, in a 1\u20131 [[Exhibition game|friendly]] draw with [[Germany national football team|Germany]].\n\nCadete was chosen for the [[UEFA Euro 1996]] finals by [[Ant\u00f3nio Oliveira (footballer, born 1952)|Ant\u00f3nio Oliveira]], after playing the decisive last match in the [[UEFA Euro 1996 qualifying|qualifying rounds]] against [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] and netting the last in a 3\u20130 win as a substitute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pt.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=226/match=50729/postmatch/lineups/index.html|title=Portugal 3\u20130 Rep\u00fablica da Irlanda|trans-title=Portugal 3\u20130 Republic of Ireland|publisher=UEFA|language=pt|date=15 November 1995|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> His final appearance was a 0\u20133 defeat to [[England national football team|England]] on 22 April 1998, in another friendly.\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n:Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foradejogo.net/player.php?player=196808270001&language=2|title=Cadete|publisher=ForaDeJogo|accessdate=3 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/jorge-paulo-cadete-santos-reis/222262/|title=Jorge Cadete|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=3 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[UEFA#Club|Europe]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other<ref group=\"lower-alpha\">Includes the [[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]]</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"9\"|[[Sporting CP|Sporting]]\n|[[1987\u201388 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1987\u201388]]\n|6||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0||0||0||8||0\n|-\n|[[1989\u201390 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1989\u201390]]\n|29||7||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||33||4\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1990\u201391]]\n|30||3||3||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||10||6||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||43||10\n|-\n|[[1991\u201392 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1991\u201392]]\n|34||25||2||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||38||26\n|-\n|[[1992\u201393 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1992\u201393]]\n|34||17||5||4||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||41||22\n|-\n|[[1993\u201394 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1993\u201394]]\n|26||10||4||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||6||4||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||36||15\n|-\n|[[1994\u201395 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1994\u201395]]\n|2||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||3||0\n|-\n|[[1995\u201396 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1995\u201396]]\n|3||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||1||0||4||0\n|-\n!Total\n!164!!62!!16!!7!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!22!!11!!1!!0!!203!!80\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Vit\u00f3ria F.C.|Vit\u00f3ria Set\u00fabal]] (loan)\n|[[1988\u201389 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1988\u201389]]\n|29||8||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||30||8\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Brescia Calcio|Brescia]] (loan)\n|[[1994\u201395 Serie A|1994\u201395]]\n|13||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||13||1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]\n|[[1995\u201396 Scottish Premier Division|1995\u201396]]\n|6||5||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||6||5\n|-\n|[[1996\u201397 Scottish Premier Division|1996\u201397]]\n|31||25||5||2||3||5||4||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||43||33\n|-\n!Total\n!37!!30!!5!!2!!3!!5!!4!!1!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!49!!38\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]]\n|[[1997\u201398 La Liga|1997\u201398]]\n|29||7||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||30||7\n|-\n|[[1998\u201399 La Liga|1998\u201399]]\n|7||1||||||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||11||1\n|-\n!Total\n!36!!8!!1!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!4!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!41!!8\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]\n|[[1998\u201399 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1998\u201399]]\n|16||3||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||17||3\n|-\n|[[1999\u20132000 Primeira Liga|1999\u20132000]]\n|3||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||5||0\n|-\n|[[2002\u201303 Primeira Liga|2002\u201303]]\n|0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n!Total\n!19!!3!!2!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!1!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!22!!3\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (loan)\n|[[1999\u20132000 FA Premier League|1999\u20132000]]\n|7||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||7||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[C.F. Estrela da Amadora|Estrela Amadora]] (loan)\n|[[2000\u201301 Primeira Liga|2000\u201301]]\n|21||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||22||0\n|-\n|[[2001\u201302 Segunda Liga|2001\u201302]]\n|7||2||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||7||2\n|-\n!Total\n!28!!2!!1!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!29!!2\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n|[[2003\u201304 Scottish Premier League|2003\u201304]]\n|5||0||||||||||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||5||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[C.D. Pinhalnovense|Pinhalnovense]]\n|[[2004\u201305 Segunda Divis\u00e3o B|2004\u201305]]\n|4||0||1||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||5||2\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|S\u00e3o Marcos\n|2005\u201306\n|||||||||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||||\n|-\n|2006\u201307\n|||||||||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||||\n|-\n!Total\n!!!!!!!!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!!!\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Career total\n!342!!114!!26!!11!!3!!5!!31!!12!!1!!0!!403!!142\n|}\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n===International===\n{{Ig header|n=Jorge Cadete}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=3038|title=Jorge Cadete|publisher=European Football|accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref>\n{{Ig match\n| n= 1\n| d= 20 February 1991\n| st=Est\u00e1dio das Antas| ci=Porto | co=Portugal\n| o=Malta\n| sc='''5'''\u20130\n| fr=5\u20130\n| comp=[[UEFA Euro 1992 qualifying|Euro 1992 qualifying]]}}\n{{Ig match\n| n= 2\n| d= 28 April 1993\n| st=Est\u00e1dio da Luz (1954)| ci=Lisbon | co=Portugal\n| o=Scotland\n| sc='''2'''\u20130\n| fr=5\u20130\n| comp=[[1994 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|1994 World Cup qualification]]}}\n{{Ig match\n| n= 3\n| d= 28 April 1993\n| st=Est\u00e1dio da Luz (1954)| ci=Lisbon| co=Portugal\n| o=Scotland\n| sc='''5'''\u20130\n| fr=5\u20130\n| comp=1994 World Cup qualification}}\n{{Ig match\n| n= 4\n| d= 19 June 1993\n| st=Est\u00e1dio do Bessa| ci=Porto| co=Portugal\n| o=Malta\n| sc='''4'''\u20130\n| fr=4\u20130\n| comp=1994 World Cup qualification}}\n{{Ig match\n| n= 5\n| d= 15 November 1995\n| st=Est\u00e1dio da Luz (1954)| ci=Lisbon| co=Portugal\n| o=Republic of Ireland\n| sc='''3'''\u20130\n| fr=3\u20130\n| comp=[[UEFA Euro 1996 qualifying|Euro 1996 qualifying]]}}\n{{Ig footer}}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Sporting'''\n*[[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]]: [[1995 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|1995]]<ref name=Supercup/>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[Bola de Prata (Portugal)|Bola de Prata]]: [[1992\u201393 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1992\u201393]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesp/porttops.html|title=Portugal \u2013 List of Topscorers|publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]|first1=Paulo|last1=Claro|first2=Simon|last2=Preston|first3=Jo\u00e3o|last3=Nunes|first4=Roberto|last4=Di Maggio|accessdate=5 April 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Scottish Premier League]]: [[List of Scottish football champions|Top Scorer]] [[1996\u201397 Scottish Premier Division|1996\u201397]]<ref name=Scorer/>\n*[[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]]: Top Scorer [[1992\u201393 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|1992\u201393]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*{{BDFutbol|1351}}\n*[https://www.fpf.pt/Jogadores/Jogador/playerId/1126422 National team data] {{in lang|pt}}\n*{{NFT|14183}}\n*{{FIFA player|95094}}\n\n{{Portugal Squad 1996 Euro Cup}}\n{{Primeira Liga top scorers}}\n{{Scottish First Division top scorers}}\n{{Ta\u00e7a de Portugal top scorers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cadete, Jorge}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cabo Delgado Province]]\n[[Category:Colonial people in Mozambique]]\n[[Category:Portuguese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:LigaPro players]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Second Division players]]\n[[Category:Sporting CP footballers]]\n[[Category:Vit\u00f3ria F.C. players]]\n[[Category:S.L. Benfica footballers]]\n[[Category:C.F. Estrela da Amadora players]]\n[[Category:C.D. Pinhalnovense players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Brescia Calcio players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Celtic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Partick Thistle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:RC Celta de Vigo players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Portugal youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Portugal under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Portugal international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1996 players]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Scottish league football top scorers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name = Jorge Cadete\n|image = \n|fullname = Jorge Paulo Cadete Santos Reis\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|8|27|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Pemba, Mozambique|Pemba]], [[Portuguese Mozambique|Mozambique]]\n|height = {{convert|1.80|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n|youthyears1 = 1983\u20131984 | youthclubs1 = Acad\u00e9mica Santar\u00e9m\n|youthyears2 = 1984\u20131987 | youthclubs2 = [[Sporting CP]]\n|years1 = 1987\u20131995 | clubs1 = [[Sporting CP]] | caps1 = 164 | goals1 = 62\n|years2 = 1988\u20131989 | clubs2 = \u2192 [[Vit\u00f3ria F.C.|Vit\u00f3ria Set\u00fabal]] (loan) | caps2 = 29 | goals2 = 8\n|years3 = 1994\u20131995 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Brescia Calcio|Brescia]] (loan) | caps3 = 13 | goals3 = 1\n|years4 = 1996\u20131997 | clubs4 = [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] | caps4 = 37 | goals4 = 30\n|years5 = 1997\u20131998 | clubs5 = [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]] | caps5 = 36 | goals5 = 8\n|years6 = 1999\u20132003 | clubs6 = [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] | caps6 = 19 | goals6 = 3\n|years7 = 2000 | clubs7 = \u2192 [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (loan) | caps7 = 7 | goals7 = 0\n|years8 = 2000\u20132001 | clubs8 = \u2192 [[C.F. Estrela da Amadora|Estrela Amadora]] (loan) | caps8 = 28 | goals8 = 2\n|years9 = 2004 | clubs9 = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] | caps9 = 5 | goals9 = 0\n|years10 = 2004\u20132005 | clubs10 = [[C.D. Pinhalnovense|Pinhalnovense]] | caps10 = 4 | goals10 = 0\n|years11 = 2005\u20132007 | clubs11 = S\u00e3o Marcos | caps11 = | goals11 = \n|totalcaps = 342 | totalgoals = 114\n|nationalyears1 = 1989 | nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 2 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n|nationalyears2 = 1990\u20131998 | nationalteam2 =[[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] | nationalcaps2 = 33 | nationalgoals2 = 5\n}}\n'''Jorge Paulo Cadete Santos Reis''' (born 27 August 1968), known as '''Cadete''', is a Portuguese former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]].\n\nBorn to [[White African#Former Portuguese colonies|Portuguese parents in Mozambique]], he was groomed in [[Sporting CP|Sporting]]'s prolific youth system, and later was noted while at [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] as he led the goalscoring charts in [[1996\u201397 Scottish Premier Division|1996\u201397]].\n\nCadete amassed [[Primeira Liga]] totals of 233 matches and 73 goals over 12 seasons. A [[Portugal national football team|Portuguese international]] throughout the 90s, he represented the nation at [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 1996]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career / Sporting===\nBorn in [[Pemba, Mozambique|Pemba]], [[Portuguese Mozambique]], Cadete began his footballing career with Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Acad\u00e9mica de Santar\u00e9m at age 15, scoring an impressive 43 goals in just 18 games.<ref name=Expresso>{{cite news|url=https://tribunaexpresso.pt/a-casa-as-costas/2017-10-14-Jorge-Cadete-Nao-sou-nenhum-deficiente.-Tenho-duas-maos-dois-bracinhos-nao-desisti-de-dar-a-volta-a-tudo|title=Jorge Cadete: \u201cN\u00e3o sou nenhum deficiente. Tenho duas m\u00e3os, dois bracinhos, n\u00e3o desisti de dar a volta a tudo\u201d|trans-title=Jorge Cadete: \u201cI'm not handicapped. I have two hands, two little arms, I have not given up on turning things around\u201d|newspaper=[[Expresso (newspaper)|Expresso]]|first=Alexandra|last=Sim\u00f5es de Abreu|language=pt|date=14 October 2017|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref> His exploits alerted [[Primeira Liga]] giants [[Sporting CP]] and [[S.L. Benfica]], with the former winning the race to sign the promising youngster.<ref name=\"Celta\">{{cite web|url=http://www.yojugueenelcelta.com/2008/04/jorge-cadete.html|title=Jorge Cadete|publisher=Yo Jugu\u00e9 en el Celta|language=es|date=8 April 2008|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref>\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[File:Scpxbelenenses.gif|thumb|left|300px|Jorge Cadete with [[Sporting Clube de Portugal]]]] -->\n\nCadete broke into the senior team in [[1987\u201388 Primeira Liga|1987\u201388]], starting in four of his six appearances and subsequently being sent on loan to fellow league club [[Vit\u00f3ria F.C.]] for [[1988\u201389 Primeira Liga|the following season]], helping the [[Set\u00fabal]]-based side to the fifth place. He thus returned to [[Lisbon]], where he would play for the following five years uninterrupted and in the [[1992\u201393 Primeira Liga|1992\u201393 campaign]] he was the national championship's top-scorer with 18 goals.<ref name=Expresso/>\n\nTowards the end of his time at Sporting, Cadete was loaned out again in November 1994, this time to Italy's [[Brescia Calcio]]. He only managed one [[Serie A]] goal during his stint,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contra-ataque.it/2016/05/27/cadete-brescia-europei-bidone.html|title=Pacchi Europei: Cadete, il Brescia peggiore di sempre e la comparsata ad Euro \u201996|trans-title=European parcels: Cadete, worst-ever Brescia and cameo at Euro \u201996|publisher=Contra Ataque|first=Salvatore|last=Lavino|language=it|date=27 May 2016|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> returning subsequently to the [[Est\u00e1dio Jos\u00e9 Alvalade]] and featuring in [[1995 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|the first leg]] of the [[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]] against [[FC Porto]] in August 1995.<ref name=Supercup>{{cite web|url=http://www.zerozero.pt/jogo.php?id=47003|title=Sporting 0\u20130 FC Porto|publisher=Zerozero|language=pt|date=6 August 1995|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy early 1996, especially after the sacking of manager [[Bobby Robson]] and the arrival of [[Carlos Queiroz]], Cadete was completely out of favour at Sporting and made no more appearances for them. He amassed competitive totals for the club of 203 games and 81 goals.<ref name=Expresso/>\n\n===Celtic===\nOn 24 February 1996, Cadete was introduced at [[Celtic Park]], [[Glasgow]] to supporters before [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]'s league match against [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/celtics-four-sight-1321029.html|title=Celtic's four sight|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|first=David|last=Dick|date=25 February 1996|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref> However, due to lengthy negotiations between Celtic and Sporting and issues with registering the player, his transfer was not finalised until April, and turned out to be controversial: despite being signed prior to the transfer deadline, the [[Scottish Football Association]] delayed processing his registration in time for the [[Scottish Cup]] semi-finals against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] at [[Hampden Park]], and following a complaint from Celtic chairman [[Fergus McCann]], SFA chief [[Jim Farry]] was eventually relieved of his duties after being found guilty of deliberately holding back the player's registration.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/288283.stm Football SFA boss suspended]; [[BBC Sport]], 1 March 1999</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/farry-s-fall-from-grace-1-1304383|title=Farry's fall from grace|newspaper=[[The Scotsman]]|date=21 February 2009|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref> His eventual debut came at home against [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] as he came [[Substitute (association football)|off the bench]] to score his team's fifth goal in a 5\u20130 win, thus becoming an instant hit;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/cadete-boosts-celtic-title-chase-1302941.html|title=Cadete boosts Celtic title chase|newspaper=The Independent|first=David|last=McKinney|date=1 April 1996|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref> the loud roar generated by the fans celebrating his goal blew out [[BBC Radio 5 Live|BBC Radio 5]]'s microphones, who had been covering the game UK wide on radio, and they went off air for a short time until it was repaired.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celticunderground.net/debut-days-jorge-cadete/|title=Debut Days \u2013 Jorge Cadete|publisher=The Celtic Underground|date=19 November 2016|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nCadete's [[1996\u201397 Scottish Premier Division|only full season]] in [[Scotland]] was unarguably the greatest of his career, with the player finishing the year as the country's top scorer with 38 goals in 47 appearances in all competitions, without the aid of [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kicks]].<ref name=Scorer>{{cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/celtic/leeds-tried-to-sign-jorge-cadete-from-celtic-for-9m-1-4588343|title=Leeds \u2018tried to sign Jorge Cadete from Celtic for \u00a39m\u2019|newspaper=The Scotsman|first=Craig|last=Forbes|date=16 October 2017|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> Despite this, his team lost the league championship to arch-rivals Rangers, and he played his last match against [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], bowing to the fans before kissing the turf.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/jan/29/jorge-cadete-portugal-celtic-state-benefits|title=Jorge Cadete: the former Celtic striker who lost everything|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|first=Ewan|last=Murray|date=29 January 2014|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nAlong with [[Pierre van Hooijdonk]] and [[Paolo Di Canio]], Cadete became embroiled in contractual disputes with the club, and was labelled as one of the \"Three Amigos\" by McCann. He remained a Celtic player over the summer, but fled back to Portugal citing mental health issues and a failure to adjust to life in Scotland without his family; his requests for a transfer were eventually granted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/mccann-knocks-three-amigos-1-526878|title=McCann knocks three amigos|newspaper=The Scotsman|date=10 May 2001|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===To Spain and beyond===\nAfter failing to show for pre-season training, Cadete was transferred to [[RC Celta de Vigo]] of [[La Liga]] for a fee of around \u00a33,500,000.<ref name=\"Celta\"/> He played [[1997\u201398 La Liga|one full season]] for the [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicians]], and scored on his debut on 27 September 1997 in a 3\u20133 draw away to [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-no-end-in-sight-to-milan-slump-1241850.html|title=Football: No end in sight to Milan slump|newspaper=The Independent|first=Rupert|last=Metcalf|date=28 September 1997|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> He moved to Benfica alongside former Celtic teammate van Hooijdonk in January 1999, and a year later he returned to the United Kingdom, joining newly promoted [[Premier League]] side [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] on loan until the end of [[1999\u20132000 FA Premier League|the campaign]]; he made his debut as a substitute in a 1\u20131 draw with [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] at [[Valley Parade]], and was described as having an \"instant impact\" in that game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/feb/28/match.bradford|title=Cadete has instant effect on Bradford's survival instincts|newspaper=The Guardian|first=Adam|last=Sills|date=28 February 2000|accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor [[2000\u201301 Primeira Liga|2000\u201301]], Cadete was loaned to the Lisbon-based [[C.F. Estrela da Amadora]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/futebol/nacional/interior.aspx?content_id=37070|title=Cadete e Lu\u00eds Carlos assinam pelo Estrela da Amadora|trans-title=Cadete and Lu\u00eds Carlos sign for Estrela da Amadora|newspaper=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]|language=pt|date=23 June 2000|accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref> As newly promoted Scottish side [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] looked for a striker to bolster its chances of top-flight survival, he almost made a return to the country, but the proposed January switch fell through and he remained in Estrela, subsequently seeing out his Benfica contract after claiming unpaid wages.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/benfica/detalhe/cadete-vai-rescindir-contrato-com-o-benfica|title=Cadete vai rescindir contrato com o Benfica|trans-title=Cadete will terminate contract with Benfica|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=24 October 2000|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement / Return to football and Scotland===\nFollowing his release from Benfica, Cadete found himself without a club. After failing to find a new team he retired from football at the relatively young age of 33, going on to make an appearance on the celebrity version of the [[Big Brother (TV series)|Big Brother]] reality TV show.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cmjornal.xl.pt/noticia.aspx?channelid=00000133-0000-0000-0000-000000000133&contentid=B29B4580-947A-426F-B890-D4256A978E63|title=Cadete luta contra falta de dinheiro|trans-title=Cadete struggles against shortage of money|newspaper=[[Correio da Manh\u00e3]]|language=pt|date=29 November 2008|accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[File:jorgeII.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] Jorge Cadete on signing for Partick Thistle]] -->\nAt the start of 2003\u201304 season, aged 35, Cadete decided to come out of retirement. He returned to Scotland to make a guest appearance on [[Tam Cowan]]'s Scottish football show \"[[Offside (TV Show)|Offside]]\", where he spoke of his love for Celtic and how he regretted leaving; he also invited Celtic boss [[Martin O'Neill]] to give him a trial for his former club.\n\nCadete's return to the public eye in Scotland prompted rookie co-managers [[Gerry Britton]] and [[Derek Whyte]] to take a gamble on the striker. He signed a short-term contract for top division relegation battlers [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] in late January 2004, ending his 18-month exile from the game; the move was controversial however, as he had already agreed to sign for [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]], even being photographed in the team shirt by the media.\n\nCadete made his debut for the ''Jags'' on 22 February against former club Celtic, and received a mixed reception, with jeers from some Celtic fans as he came off the bench due to the manner of his departure six years earlier.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/scot_prem/3505203.stm Partick Thistle 1\u20134 Celtic]; BBC Sport, 22 February 2004</ref> Shortly after, he returned to old ways when he reported back for training 24 hours late, and was subsequently disciplined by the club;<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/3527311.stm Cadete back with Thistle]; BBC Sport, 3 March 2004</ref> he did not manage to score for Thistle in four months, and was not offered a contract extension.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/3495529.stm Thistle let Cadete go]; BBC Sport, 20 March 2004</ref>\n\n===Later years===\nCadete returned to his country in the [[2004\u201305 Segunda Divis\u00e3o B|2004\u201305 campaign]], joining [[Portuguese Second Division|third division]]'s [[C.D. Pinhalnovense]]. He cited the major factor in signing for the club was working with coach [[Paco Fortes]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cmjornal.pt/desporto/detalhe/nova-etapa-para-cadete|title=Nova etapa para Cadete|trans-title=New lease of life for Cadete|newspaper=Correio da Manh\u00e3|language=pt|date=6 August 2004|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the following two years, Cadete played amateur football in the [[Beja, Portugal|Beja]] region, with FC S\u00e3o Marcos in S\u00e3o Marcos da Ataboeira, [[Castro Verde]], being rejoined by some former professionals in the country, including Benfica and [[S.C. Farense]]'s [[Hassan Nader]]. After retiring, he faced severe economic problems.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cmjornal.pt/desporto/detalhe/jorge-cadete-sem-dinheiro-e-em-casa-dos-pais|title=Jorge Cadete sem dinheiro e em casa dos pais|trans-title=Jorge Cadete with no money and in his parents' house|newspaper=Correio da Manh\u00e3|language=pt|date=22 January 2014|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian\"/>\n\nOn 23 July 2015, Cadete was appointed [[director of football]] of U.F.C. Almeirim in [[Santar\u00e9m, Portugal|Santar\u00e9m]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/detalhe/jorge-cadete-dirigente-em-almeirim-964125.html|title=Jorge Cadete dirigente em Almeirim|trans-title=Jorge Cadete director in Almeirim|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=23 July 2015|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nCadete won 33 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for the [[Portugal national football team|Portuguese national team]] scoring five goals, 22 while at Sporting, nine while at Celtic and two as a Celta player. His first game came on 29 August 1990, in a 1\u20131 [[Exhibition game|friendly]] draw with [[Germany national football team|Germany]].\n\nCadete was chosen for the [[UEFA Euro 1996]] finals by [[Ant\u00f3nio Oliveira (footballer, born 1952)|Ant\u00f3nio Oliveira]], after playing the decisive last match in the [[UEFA Euro 1996 qualifying|qualifying rounds]] against [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] and netting the last in a 3\u20130 win as a substitute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pt.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=226/match=50729/postmatch/lineups/index.html|title=Portugal 3\u20130 Rep\u00fablica da Irlanda|trans-title=Portugal 3\u20130 Republic of Ireland|publisher=UEFA|language=pt|date=15 November 1995|accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> His final appearance was a 0\u20133 defeat to [[England national football team|England]] on 22 April 1998, in another friendly.\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foradejogo.net/player.php?player=196808270001&language=2|title=Cadete|publisher=ForaDeJogo|accessdate=3 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/jorge-paulo-cadete-santos-reis/222262/|title=Jorge Cadete|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=3 December 2017}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[UEFA#Club|Europe]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other<ref group=\"lower-alpha\">Includes the [[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]]</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"9\" valign=\"center\"|[[Sporting CP|Sporting]]\n|[[1987\u201388 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1987\u201388]]\n|6||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0||0||0||8||0\n|-\n|[[1989\u201390 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1989\u201390]]\n|29||7||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||33||4\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1